text:
With all due respect, that genuinely doesnt matter.

American chinese food is definitely different from mainland chinese dishes, but it is still definitively chinese.

Discrimination against individuals of east asian descent was extremely high for long periods of our history.  To keep out new chinese immigrants, the US implemented quotas for immigration, but left an exception for individuals with approved work in a high dining restaurant.

This lead to chinese families opening restaurants wherever possible, as a means for getting family and friends into the country with ease.  This was happening during a time period where the cost of importating authentic asian ingredients was at an extreme high.

So a large number of chinese restaurants adapted to local ingredients, while using similar flavor profiles and cooking techniques.

The nature of the loophole that chinese restaurants provided for families seeking to bring their families to North America meant that restaurants were far more cooperative than other styles of restaurant... meaning these dishes and recipes were shared en masse.

Yes, many of these are american chinese dishes.  But they are objectively a major part of chinese american history.  "Lack of authenticity" is an absurd complaint to make about any of these dishes.

We dont say "the way black americans in the south make collard greens isnt authentic to the true african recipes".  We recognize that southern style collard greens ARE an authentic dish.  With its own important impact on culinary and cultural history.
author: @marcush4741

text: ¬†@marcush4741¬† Your last statement is the only necessary statement in this diatribe. We don‚Äôt take African inspired dishes in America and call it African Food. It is either Southern, Soul, or African American. So the same is and should be true for Chinese food. Yes it‚Äôs true a lot of you don‚Äôt know about Chinese culture and their history in America, but it is culturally appropriate to call authentic Chinese food Chinese food. Because we do have authentic Chinese restaurants and dishes in America, but that food can be categorically notated to differentiate it from ‚ÄúAmeicanized‚Äù Chinese food. Which can and should be considered Chinese-American food created by people of this country with Chinese heritage but are also American and a part of this country‚Äôs history.
author: @atlnla4112

text:
¬†@atlnla4112¬†  when a person moves from china to the united states, and makes food using the processes they grew up with, they arent removed from chinese history.

When slaves were brought to the US and made collard greens as close as they could to back home, they didnt stop being african.

If an American moves to london, and makes meals close to the way he grew up, he doesnt stop being american.

These dishes werent invented by americans trying to mimic chinese dishes.  They were made by chinese people who emmigrated.  The chinese individuals who invented these dishes would be insulted to hesr people saying "thats not chinese, its american".
author: @marcush4741

text: ¬†@marcush4741¬† you just made two opposing statements. A dish can‚Äôt be considered Chinese if a person from China doesn‚Äôt or can‚Äôt recognize it as a dish that has never been served in China, a Mexican person wouldn‚Äôt call a dish Mexican if no one in Mexico would recognize that dish. An African person seeing collard greens would recognize it as something similar to a dish that may be served in a certain area in Africa but they wouldn‚Äôt call it an African dish. So again, a dish like kung pao chicken, there is a dish served in China even with a similar name as is in the US. But if you gave a fortune cookie to a Chinese person and told them it was Chinese, that would be insulting and they would look at you like you were crazy. The person is a who or whatever they are, which is a different point. The food is not the person. If an American goes to London and makes meatloaf, that‚Äôs a fairly American dish, but if that person makes Haggis we wouldn‚Äôt say he‚Äôs making American food. Pretty much everything in America is ‚Äúinspired by‚Äù something from some other culture or country, but it can also be uniquely American. That‚Äôs why we say Asian American or Chinese American, Mexican American or Latin American, Colombian American or Latin America, European American; what they create is uniquely both, not chosen to be one or the other when it has no relation to their country of origin. Just ask a Mexican person if a crunch wrap supreme is a Mexican dish.

text:
¬†@atlnla4112¬†  im glad you mentioned the hamburger.  Im jewish, and my family comes from Germany.  This is the one specific food I cant be BS'd about.

Hamburgers have a weird origin, and making the comparison is intellectually dishonest.

The hamburg steak predates the hamburger.  But it was made with ground AND chunk beef, and was served with gravy.  The "hamburger" sandwich, on the other hand, has its origins in the 1880s.

Due to similar people creating it around roughly the same time, it has multiple origin stories.  Of the 5 or so popular stories related to its origin, only one traces any linneage back to hamburg, and it's through the hamburg steak... not the hamburg steak between two patties.

The name for the hamburger was popularized after the eerie county fair, in which frank and charles menches (residents of hamburg, OHIO) replaced their pork sausage sandwiches with beef.

While this is definitively NOT the first hamburger ever made it was exactly when the name became synonymous with the food.  Every other instance of ground beef between two buns was ALSO done by an american with no german citizenship OR german national origin.

The hamburger is american.  Because it was made by americans.  In america.  The name comes from Hamburg, OHIO.

If the people making the hamburger were  German, I would 100% argue that the food is of german origin.  The same way we call french inspired dishes french, if the chef comes from france and quotes their french experience as the reason for the dish.

The hamburger isnt german because it was invented by americans in america who had no ties to germany.

Many of these chinese dishes were invented by people who we KNOW were chinese in culture, heart, and citizenship.

Theyre not comparable.
author: @marcush4741

text:
¬†@atlnla4112¬† comparing my hamburger stats with the other dish you mentioned... there are two origin stories.

Chef Peng Cheng-kuei and chef T.T.  both are chefs trained in China.  Peng claimed to have been inspired by hunan cooking. Wang claim the same.  Both are from china (though chef Peng is from taiwan and may not fall into the original "mainland china" claim, depending on your politics).

Both were chinese nationals when they claimed to have invented their dish, and both were originally from chinese territory.  One claims the invention in china.  The other claims the invention in NY (as a chinese national, claiming his training in hunan cooking).

Compared to the hamburger... only one hamburger origin story traces itself back to hamburg germany, and its dish is objectively different from what would become the hamburger... and most scholars dont take that seiously because EARLIER claims were made by americans who were full US citizens, didnt have german origin, and claimed the name from hamburg OHIO... in the US.

The two dishes cannot be compared with any level of intellectual honesty.
author: @marcush4741
